"Let's get back to the room with the port. It's the only place from which we might attract attention."\par
But they didn't.\par
In that last room, the port was no longer blue and full of sky. It was black, and hard yellow pin-point stars spelled space.\par
There was a dull, double thud, as two bodies collapsed separately into two chairs.\par
Alfred Lanning met Dr. Calvin just outside his office. He lit a nervous cigar and motioned her in.\par
He said, "Well, Susan, we've come pretty far, and Robertson's getting jumpy. What are you doing with The Brain?"\par
Susan Calvin spread her hands, "It's no use getting impatient. The Brain is worth more than anything we forfeit on this deal."\par
"But you've been questioning it for two months."\par
The psychologist's voice was flat, but somehow dangerous, "You would rather run this yourself?"\par
"Now you know what I meant."\par
"Oh, I suppose I do," Dr. Calvin rubbed her hands nervously. "It isn't easy. I've been pampering it and probing it gently, and I haven't gotten anywhere yet. Its' reactions aren't normal. Its answers -- they're queer, somehow. But nothing I can put my finger on yet. And you see, until we know what's wrong, we must just tiptoe our way through. I can never tell what simple question or remark will just ... push him over ... and then -- Well, and then we'll have on our hands a completely useless Brain. Do you want to face that?"\par
"Well, it can't break the First Law."\par
"I would have thought so, but-"\par
"You're not even sure of that?" Lanning was profoundly shocked.\par
"Oh, I can't be sure of anything, Alfred-"\par
The alarm system raised its fearful clangor with a horrifying suddenness. Lanning clicked on communications with an almost paralytic spasm. The breathless words froze him.\par
He said, "Susan ... you heard that ... the ship's gone. I sent those two field men inside half an hour ago. You'll have to see The Brain again."\par
Susan Calvin said with enforced calm, "Brain, what happened to the ship?"\par
The Brain said happily, "The ship I built, Miss Susan?"\par
"That's right. What has happened to it?"\par
"Why, nothing at all. The two men that were supposed to test it were inside, and we were all set. So I sent it off."\par
"Oh -- Well, that's nice." The psychologist felt some difficulty in breathing. "Do you think they'll be all right?"\par
"Right as anything, Miss Susan. I've taken care of it all. It's a bee-yootiful ship."\par
"Yes, Brain, it is beautiful, but you think they have enough food, don't you? They'll be comfortable?"\par
"Plenty of food."\par
"This business might be a shock to them, Brain. Unexpected, you know."\par
The Brain tossed it off, "They'll be all right. It ought to be interesting for them."\par
"Interesting? How?"\par
"Just interesting," said The Brain, slyly.\par
"Susan," whispered Lanning in a fuming whisper, "ask him if death comes into it. Ask him what the dangers are."\par
Susan Calvin's expression contorted with fury, "Keep quiet!" In a shaken voice, she said to The Brain, "We can communicate with the ship, can't we Brain?"\par
"Oh, they can hear you if you call by radio. I've taken care of that."\par
"Thanks. That's all for now."\par
